# bt2iap — `/etc/bluetooth/main.conf` patch

This document describes the BlueZ daemon configuration overrides required so the
Raspberry Pi Zero 2 W can act as a persistently-discoverable A2DP sink that any
phone can pair to without on-device confirmation (no display / no keypad, car
install).

Target file on Pi: `/etc/bluetooth/main.conf` (shipped by the `bluez` package).

## Why each key

| Key | Value | Reason |
|-----|-------|--------|
| `Name` | `bt2iap` | Friendly name shown to the phone during scan / pairing. |
| `Class` | `0x240404` | Device class: Major = Audio/Video (0x04), Minor = Car Audio (0x08 nibble through standard encoding → car audio / hands-free / headset bundle). Encoded as `0x240404` per the Bluetooth assigned-numbers "Audio / HeadUnit" profile so a phone recognises us as a car stereo rather than a generic computer. |
| `DiscoverableTimeout` | `0` | `0` = never time out. The Pi is always discoverable while powered. |
| `PairableTimeout` | `0` | `0` = never time out. Pairing window stays open. |
| `JustWorksRepairing` | `always` | Accept Just-Works re-pair requests from a previously bonded device without user prompting (needed because the Pi is headless in a car dash). |
| `AutoEnable` (`[Policy]`) | `true` | On boot, BlueZ auto-powers every controller (no manual `power on` needed after every reboot). |
| `AutoEnable` (`[General]`) | `true` | Redundant guard for older / forked BlueZ variants that read the key from `[General]`. Harmless on current BlueZ. |

## Snippet to merge

The block below is what `bootstrap.sh` (future T2 extension) will append / merge
into `/etc/bluetooth/main.conf`. It is wrapped in sentinel comments so the
merge is idempotent.

```ini
# --- begin bt2iap ---
[General]
Name = bt2iap
Class = 0x240404
DiscoverableTimeout = 0
PairableTimeout = 0
JustWorksRepairing = always
AutoEnable = true

[Policy]
AutoEnable = true
# --- end bt2iap ---
```

Note: BlueZ tolerates repeated `[General]` section headers in the same file;
later values override earlier ones. The sentinel block is therefore safe to
append even if the shipped `main.conf` already contains a `[General]` section.

## Idempotent merge pattern (for bootstrap.sh T2 extension)

The bootstrap script must treat this patch like the other sentinel-guarded
merges already used for `/boot/config.txt`. Reference pattern:

```bash
BT_MAIN_CONF="/etc/bluetooth/main.conf"
BT_MAIN_PATCH="${BT2IAP_ROOT}/bluetooth/main.conf.patch.block"   # pure .ini payload, no markdown

SENTINEL_BEGIN="# --- begin bt2iap ---"
SENTINEL_END="# --- end bt2iap ---"

if grep -qF "${SENTINEL_BEGIN}" "${BT_MAIN_CONF}" 2>/dev/null; then
  log "${BT_MAIN_CONF}: bt2iap block already present, skip"
else
  log "${BT_MAIN_CONF}: appending bt2iap block"
  {
    printf '\n%s\n' "${SENTINEL_BEGIN}"
    cat "${BT_MAIN_PATCH}"
    printf '%s\n' "${SENTINEL_END}"
  } >> "${BT_MAIN_CONF}"
fi
```

Re-running bootstrap.sh after the block is in place is a no-op: the `grep -qF`
on the begin-sentinel short-circuits.

To remove (if the patch ever needs to be revised):

```bash
sed -i '/# --- begin bt2iap ---/,/# --- end bt2iap ---/d' /etc/bluetooth/main.conf
```

Then re-run bootstrap.sh to re-insert the current version.

### Alternative: per-key merge (not used)

For reference only — this is the awk pattern that would replace individual
keys in-place instead of appending a sentinel block. We deliberately do NOT
use this because it makes rollbacks harder:

```awk
# NOT USED — documented for completeness.
# Updates a single key within [General]; inserts if missing.
awk -v section='[General]' -v key='Name' -v val='bt2iap' '
  BEGIN { in_sec=0; wrote=0 }
  /^\[/ { if (in_sec && !wrote) { print key " = " val; wrote=1 }
          in_sec = ($0 == section) ? 1 : 0 }
  in_sec && $0 ~ "^[[:space:]]*"key"[[:space:]]*=" { print key " = " val; wrote=1; next }
  { print }
  END { if (in_sec && !wrote) print key " = " val }
' "${BT_MAIN_CONF}" > "${BT_MAIN_CONF}.new" && mv "${BT_MAIN_CONF}.new" "${BT_MAIN_CONF}"
```

The sentinel-block approach above is the canonical one.

## Companion systemd drop-in: suppress SAP plugin

Pi Zero 2 W has no SAP (SIM Access Profile) hardware. When bluetoothd starts
with the default plugin set it logs `Failed to init sap plugin` on every boot.
Harmless but noisy, and it can delay `bluetooth.service` going `active`.

Recommended drop-in (bootstrap installs this in a later T2 pass):

`/etc/systemd/system/bluetooth.service.d/override.conf`

```ini
# --- begin bt2iap ---
[Service]
# bluetoothd: drop SAP plugin (Pi has no SIM hardware; plugin init otherwise fails).
# Also blacklist sap so BlueZ does not attempt to auto-load it.
ExecStart=
ExecStart=/usr/lib/bluetooth/bluetoothd --noplugin=sap
# --- end bt2iap ---
```

Note: the empty `ExecStart=` line is the canonical systemd idiom for "discard
the inherited ExecStart before setting a new one". Without it, systemd rejects
the unit because multi-line `ExecStart=` is only allowed on Type=oneshot units.

Apply with:

```bash
sudo install -d /etc/systemd/system/bluetooth.service.d
sudo install -m 0644 bluetooth/bluetoothd-override.conf \
  /etc/systemd/system/bluetooth.service.d/override.conf
sudo systemctl daemon-reload
sudo systemctl restart bluetooth
```

## Verification (on Pi, post-apply)

```bash
# BlueZ read the overrides:
sudo systemctl restart bluetooth
bluetoothctl show | grep -E 'Name|Class|Powered|Discoverable|Pairable'

# Expected:
#   Name: bt2iap
#   Class: 0x00240404
#   Powered: yes
#   Discoverable: yes
#   Pairable: yes
```

If `Class` reads back as `0x000000` the controller did not apply the config —
check `journalctl -u bluetooth -n 100` for parser errors.
